rson named him Connecticut's first federal judge","body":"Thomas Jefferson appointed him the first U.S. District Judge for the District of Connecticut in 1806; he served until his death twenty years later. He had earlier represented Connecticut in the Continental Congress (1787-1788) and helped ratify the U.S. Constitution at the state convention."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"His daughter married Eli Whitney","body":"His daughter Henrietta Frances Edwards married inventor Eli Whitney in 1817. Their daughter Henrietta Whitney Edwards later married Prof. Worthington Hooker in 1855 — reuniting the Hooker and Edwards lines through Thomas Hooker."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"His nephew Aaron Burr was six years younger","body":"His older sister Esther Edwards married Rev. Aaron Burr Sr.; their son Aaron Burr Jr. became Vice President and was only six years younger than Pierpont. The two were uncle and nephew but more like brothers in age."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"First Grand Master of Masons in Connecticut","body":"He was a Freemason in Hiram Lodge No. 1 in New Haven and became the first Grand Master of the Grand Lodge of Connecticut. The Grand Lodge still honors distinguished members with a medal in his name."},{"number":5,"category":"career","header":"Bought Richfield Township in Ohio's Western Reserve","body":"He invested £60,000 in the Connecticut Land Company in 1795 — five percent of the company — and was one of seven investors who purchased Richfield Township in Ohio. He sent his son John Stark Edwards as his first agent in the Western Reserve."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","related_id":"HD2925","display_label":"Newton settled the Ohio township he had bought.","link_text":"John Newton"},{"type":"historical_connection","related_id":"H00443","display_label":"Both Hooker descendants shaped the Western Reserve — land and education","link_text":"Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles"},{"